WEBVTT

00:02.498 --> 00:08.769
The scripture reading today is from the book of Genesis, chapter 25, verses 19 to 34.

00:08.809 --> 00:14.479
This is the account of the family line of Abraham's son Isaac.

00:15.701 --> 00:27.922
Abraham became the father of Isaac, and Isaac was 40 years old when he married Rebecca, daughter of Beth Ewell, the Aramean from Baden Aram, and sister of Laban, the Aramean.

00:28.930 --> 00:32.995
Isaac prayed to the Lord on behalf of his wife because she was childless.

00:33.836 --> 00:37.781
The Lord answered his prayer and his wife, Rebecca, became pregnant.

00:38.542 --> 00:43.969
The babies jostled each other within her and she said, why is this happening to me?

00:44.870 --> 00:46.772
So she went to inquire of the Lord.

00:47.633 --> 00:54.782
The Lord said to her, two nations are in your womb and two peoples from within you will be separated.

00:55.583 --> 00:58.066
One people will be stronger than the other.

00:58.338 --> 01:00.521
and the older will serve the younger.

01:00.541 --> 01:06.469
When the time came for her to give birth, there were twin boys in her womb.

01:07.531 --> 01:12.217
The first to come out was red, and his whole body was like a hairy garment.

01:12.818 --> 01:14.240
So they named him Esau.

01:15.321 --> 01:20.809
After this, his brother came out with his hand grasping Esau's heel.

01:21.510 --> 01:22.972
So he was named Jacob.

01:23.913 --> 01:27.378
Isaac was 60 years old when Rebecca gave birth to them.

01:28.130 --> 01:37.519
The boys grew up, and Esau became a skillful hunter, a man of the open country, while Jacob was content to stay at home among the tents.

01:38.860 --> 01:44.566
Isaac, who had a taste for wild game, loved Esau, but Rebecca loved Jacob.

01:45.647 --> 01:51.312
Once, when Jacob was cooking some stew, Esau came in from the open country, famished.

01:51.913 --> 01:56.117
He said to Jacob, quick, let me have some of that red stew.

01:56.537 --> 01:57.618
I'm famished.

01:58.210 --> 02:00.693
That is why he was also called Edom.

02:01.775 --> 02:05.179
Jacob replied, first, sell me your birthright.

02:06.420 --> 02:08.563
Look, I'm about to die, Esau said.

02:08.984 --> 02:10.826
What good is the birthright to me?

02:10.866 --> 02:13.790
But Jacob said swear to me first.

02:14.651 --> 02:18.355
So he swore an oath to him, selling his birthright to Jacob.

02:19.357 --> 02:23.282
Then Jacob gave Esau some bread and some lentil stew.

02:23.302 --> 02:26.706
He ate and drank, then got up and left.

02:26.914 --> 02:29.398
So Esau despised his birthright.

02:30.239 --> 02:31.541
This is the word of the Lord.

02:31.601 --> 02:33.344
Thanks be to God.

02:39.114 --> 02:43.841
Good to see you all today.

02:43.861 --> 02:44.362
My name is Pete.

02:44.382 --> 02:50.131
I'm one of the pastors here and really glad that you're with us, especially if you're new or just visiting.

02:50.392 --> 02:51.954
Good to be together today.

02:52.226 --> 02:55.671
We are working our way through the book of Genesis this summer.

02:56.232 --> 03:02.240
And for the past few weeks, we've been following the story of Abraham and his family.

03:02.941 --> 03:08.469
And what we're seeing is that Abraham and his family are quite a mess, right?

03:09.951 --> 03:17.842
In fact, if you've been paying attention, every single family we've learned about is a dysfunctional family.

03:17.922 --> 03:22.108
If you think your family is messed up, just read Genesis and you'll feel better.

03:22.468 --> 03:25.272
Like everyone in this book needs therapy desperately.

03:26.093 --> 03:30.298
And what's crazy is that it's not just Genesis, it's really the entire Bible.

03:31.600 --> 03:38.249
Sometimes we talk about trying to have a biblical marriage or a biblical family, which is great.

03:38.850 --> 03:45.298
But have you ever noticed that in the Bible, no one seems to have a biblical marriage or a biblical family?

03:45.794 --> 03:48.737
Like can you think of any model marriages in scripture?

03:49.798 --> 03:53.001
Any picture perfect families.

03:53.822 --> 03:59.207
Like we get a few glimpses here and there, but pretty much every family in the Bible is dysfunctional.

04:00.028 --> 04:01.729
Adam and Eve started pretty strong.

04:02.050 --> 04:07.135
Genesis one and two, they're doing it right, but then by chapter three, the whole thing falls apart.

04:07.635 --> 04:12.840
So I wanna remind you again that not everything that happens in the Bible is biblical.

04:13.481 --> 04:14.802
Or in other words,

04:15.106 --> 04:22.220
There's a difference between what's prescribed by the Bible and what's described by the Bible.

04:22.240 --> 04:27.150
Some passages are prescriptive, others are descriptive.

04:27.591 --> 04:37.010
I mean, some passages prescribe something about how we ought to live as followers of Jesus and other passages simply describe something that happened.

04:37.378 --> 04:38.459
just part of the story.

04:38.940 --> 04:50.931
So it's important to remember that these pictures we get in Genesis of messed up marriages and dysfunctional families are almost always descriptions of what happened rather than prescriptions of what we should do.

04:51.652 --> 04:52.152
So, make sense?

04:53.534 --> 04:53.634
Okay.

04:53.654 --> 04:58.479
So now that we've got that, we can talk about where we are in the story of Abraham and his family.

04:58.939 --> 05:06.066
So if you remember, God has promised Abraham and Sarah that he would give them a son and they would become the parents of a great nation.

05:06.626 --> 05:09.230
And after a while, they still don't have any kids.

05:09.851 --> 05:15.539
And so Abraham gets with Sarah's maidservant, Hagar, and she bears him a son named Ishmael.

05:16.060 --> 05:18.403
But that was their solution, not gods.

05:18.623 --> 05:25.453
And so God kept his promises to Abraham and Sarah and gave them a son by the name of Isaac.

05:26.094 --> 05:28.658
We looked at some of that story last week.

05:29.186 --> 05:40.303
So now Abraham has two sons, and then at the beginning of Genesis 25, we're told that after Sarah dies, Abraham marries another woman named Katura, and they have six more sons.

05:40.643 --> 05:43.588
So here's what the family tree looks like so far.

05:44.549 --> 05:55.506
Father Abraham did indeed have many sons, and it's through these eight sons that the earth is populated with all the various nations and tribes.

05:55.618 --> 06:03.667
But God chooses one of these eight sons, Isaac, the one born of Sarah, to carry the family line of his blessing.

06:04.287 --> 06:14.078
And so today, as we come to Genesis 25, we find Isaac all grown up and married to a woman named Rebecca, and they've been struggling to conceive.

06:14.699 --> 06:21.426
But then, just like he did for Isaac's parents, God answers their prayers and Rebecca becomes pregnant.

06:21.922 --> 06:29.857
And in verse 22, we find out pretty early that Rebecca sensed that there was something different about this pregnancy.

06:30.658 --> 06:35.928
It says, the babies jostled each other within her, and she said, why is this happening to me?

06:36.529 --> 06:38.974
So she went to inquire of the Lord.

06:40.036 --> 06:42.661
So at this point, she doesn't know that she has twins.

06:42.841 --> 06:45.586
She just says that there's a lot going on down there.

06:45.666 --> 06:50.912
And since there are no ultrasounds, she prays and asks God, what's happening?

06:51.652 --> 06:54.796
Any of you ladies ever carried twins before?

06:54.836 --> 06:58.039
Okay, did you ever ask, why is this happening to me?

06:59.100 --> 07:03.144
I assume, I can't imagine having one person grow in my body, let alone two.

07:05.727 --> 07:08.110
So she's asking God, what's going on?

07:08.210 --> 07:12.274
Verse 23, the Lord said to her, two nations are in your womb.

07:12.706 --> 07:15.530
and two peoples from within you will be separated.

07:16.070 --> 07:20.195
One people will be stronger than the other and the older will serve the younger.

07:20.236 --> 07:37.938
Okay, so this is when Isaac and Rebecca find out they're gonna have twins and that the wrestling she feels in her womb is just a foretaste of the conflict that will define the relationship between these two kids, not just for the rest of their lives, but for generations to come.

07:38.899 --> 07:41.202
Again, no model families in the Bible.

07:41.826 --> 07:50.639
In verse 24, when the time came for her to give birth, there were twin boys in her womb, womb.

07:51.821 --> 07:57.048
The first to come out was red, and his whole body was like a hairy garment.

07:57.509 --> 07:59.372
So they named him Esauch.

07:59.392 --> 08:04.639
So the first twin pops out, and he's red and covered in hair, which isn't normal.

08:05.841 --> 08:09.266
The only thing I can picture is that she gave birth to baby Elmo.

08:10.530 --> 08:15.018
Like that's a surprise, a little red wookie or something.

08:15.078 --> 08:21.631
And then verse 26, after this, his brother came out with his hand grasping Esau's heel.

08:22.412 --> 08:23.935
So he was named Jacob.

08:23.995 --> 08:25.518
Jacob means heel-grasper.

08:26.319 --> 08:29.445
Isaac was 60 years old when Rebecca gave birth to them.

08:30.066 --> 08:32.050
So now the family tree looks like this.

08:32.482 --> 08:47.921
Abraham has two grandsons through Isaac and Rebecca, and we'll find out that he actually has a bunch of other grandkids through his other sons, but the main storyline of the Bible flows from Abraham to Isaac to Jacob.

08:48.682 --> 08:50.224
Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.

08:50.244 --> 08:55.530
You'll see those three names grouped together and repeated all throughout the scripture.

08:56.031 --> 09:01.938
Ultimately, even Jesus himself would say that his father is the God of Abraham, Isaac,

09:02.210 --> 09:02.751
and Jacob.

09:03.592 --> 09:13.066
And so for all of their faults and flaws and failures, God uses this messed up family to bring about the Savior of the world.

09:14.608 --> 09:16.511
So maybe He can work with your family too.

09:17.933 --> 09:19.916
That's the first part of this passage.

09:20.197 --> 09:22.019
Here's what happens next, verse 27.

09:22.059 --> 09:31.954
The boys grew up and Esau became a skillful hunter, a man of the open country while Jacob was content to stay home among the tents.

09:32.482 --> 09:38.270
And so Jacob and Elmo grow up, and they turn into two pretty different types of men.

09:39.071 --> 09:42.615
And the descriptions here are really meant to be a little bit over the top.

09:43.477 --> 09:53.310
So you might say Esau is a manly man who drives a big old pickup and likes hunting and fishing and watching NASCAR and drinking bush light.

09:53.710 --> 09:55.212
He's that kind of guy, right?

09:55.653 --> 09:59.698
And then Jacob, on the other hand, is a great endorsement.

09:59.778 --> 10:03.802
He does yoga and scrolls Pinterest for fun recipes.

10:04.242 --> 10:08.686
And he loves talking with his friends and sharing a bottle of rosé.

10:09.167 --> 10:14.732
So forgive me for the stereotypes, but that is what the author is trying to do here.

10:15.213 --> 10:20.438
Describe these two brothers, not just as polar opposites, but as almost cartoonish caricatures.

10:21.218 --> 10:23.080
And it gets even worse, verse 28.

10:23.140 --> 10:29.426
Isaac, who had a taste for wild game, loved Esau, but Rebecca loved Jacob.

10:29.922 --> 10:37.054
So to pile on top of it all, Esau, the rugged Harry Hunter, is his dad's favorite because his dad likes to eat meat.

10:37.735 --> 10:43.524
And Jacob, the well-manscaped little brother, is a total mama's boy, right?

10:43.725 --> 10:46.209
And Rebecca likes him the best, okay?

10:46.229 --> 10:48.733
So these are the two characters in our story.

10:49.434 --> 10:56.786
Verse 29, once when Jacob was cooking some stew, Esau came in from the open country, famished.

10:57.346 --> 11:00.371
He said to Jacob, quick, let me have some of that red stew.

11:00.411 --> 11:01.112
I'm famished.

11:01.713 --> 11:04.717
That's why he was also called eat him.

11:04.737 --> 11:07.141
Okay, so Jacob's in the kitchen, cooking a pot of soup.

11:08.182 --> 11:11.727
Esau barges in from hunting, acting like he's starving to death.

11:12.328 --> 11:16.314
He smells what Jacob's got on the stove and says, give me some of that red stuff.

11:16.475 --> 11:18.618
That's literally what he calls it, red stuff.

11:19.279 --> 11:21.522
In Hebrew, red is eat him.

11:22.146 --> 11:33.770
So the author here is giving us a little heads up that the events that are about to go down in the next few minutes are going to define Esau's life and legacy for generations to come.

11:33.810 --> 11:43.730
That the red hairy man wanted a bowl of red stuff and from this point on he's going to be known as red.

11:44.226 --> 11:48.231
and his descendants are gonna be known as the Edomites, the Red People.

11:48.751 --> 11:52.957
So what's about to happen here has serious long-term consequences.

11:55.139 --> 12:00.546
Jacob sees how hungry his brother is and he sees it as an opportunity to take advantage of it.

12:00.566 --> 12:04.631
Verse 31, Jacob replied, first, sell me your birthright.

12:05.452 --> 12:07.554
Look, I'm about to die, Esau said.

12:07.694 --> 12:09.096
What good is a birthright to me?

12:10.658 --> 12:14.162
So what we need to know is to have the family's birthright was a really big deal.

12:14.626 --> 12:21.535
First, financially, the child with the birthright was entitled to the lion's share of the family estate.

12:22.136 --> 12:31.508
The one with the birthright would inherit two-thirds of the family's money and property, and the other third would be divided amongst the other siblings.

12:31.708 --> 12:33.551
And so the birthright meant money.

12:34.272 --> 12:36.254
Secondly, the birthright meant power.

12:36.635 --> 12:42.322
Whoever held the birthright would become the new head of the household when the father died.

12:42.594 --> 12:49.122
So they would become the new patriarch and they would control the fate and the destiny of the entire family.

12:49.142 --> 12:52.446
And so not only did the birthright give you money, but also power.

12:52.486 --> 12:54.689
Having the birthright was a big deal.

12:55.650 --> 12:58.574
So how did they decide which child got the birthright?

12:59.235 --> 12:59.555
Simple.

13:00.056 --> 13:01.458
It was the firstborn.

13:03.240 --> 13:05.403
Whoever was born first got the birthright.

13:05.423 --> 13:07.085
How many firstborns in the room?

13:08.046 --> 13:08.146
Okay?

13:08.258 --> 13:10.221
This sounds like a pretty good deal, right?

13:11.022 --> 13:11.964
I'm the oldest of four.

13:12.104 --> 13:13.827
I see no problem with this system.

13:14.508 --> 13:15.309
Makes sense to me.

13:16.951 --> 13:19.415
What if your twins are first born?

13:20.377 --> 13:22.620
Well, then it's the one that comes out first, right?

13:23.041 --> 13:27.307
So this is why the author told us that it was Esau who came out first.

13:28.068 --> 13:36.882
But we're also told that Jacob came out literally just seconds behind him gripping the heel of his first born brother.

13:37.666 --> 13:45.559
And so the picture is, from the day they were born, it's like Jacob has been grasping to get ahead of his brother.

13:46.480 --> 13:49.405
And now, after all these years, he finally gets his chance.

13:50.727 --> 13:53.531
So he tells Esau, sure, you can have as much soup as you want.

13:54.293 --> 13:56.817
Just let me have the birthright, and it's all yours.

13:58.159 --> 14:05.170
And Esau, like an idiot, says, well, I'm about to starve to death, and a birthright isn't gonna do me any good if I'm dead.

14:05.826 --> 14:08.889
So in verse 33, Jacob said, swear to me first.

14:09.450 --> 14:13.274
So Esau swore an oath to him, selling his birthright to Jacob.

14:13.874 --> 14:17.138
Then Jacob gave Esau some bread and some lentil stew.

14:17.518 --> 14:20.541
He ate and drank, then he got up and left.

14:20.561 --> 14:23.244
So Esau despised his birthright.

14:24.445 --> 14:25.627
And so Jacob's plan works.

14:26.548 --> 14:32.594
He cons his brother into giving him his birthright in exchange for a bowl of soup.

14:34.946 --> 14:38.632
So why on earth would Esa agree to this?

14:41.096 --> 14:43.139
Was he literally starving to death?

14:43.740 --> 14:49.329
Like maybe he really was minutes away from dying and this was a life or death situation.

14:50.511 --> 14:59.986
Or maybe he like had an intellectual disability and he was just too naive or simple to understand how bad of a deal this was.

15:00.066 --> 15:10.736
Like if you took a one-year-old kid and gave them a choice between a check for $100 million and a blueberry, what would they take?

15:11.557 --> 15:14.500
They would take the blueberry every single time, right?

15:14.940 --> 15:18.103
So maybe this is what we see in Esau.

15:18.123 --> 15:19.925
He's just that simple.

15:20.866 --> 15:23.989
But the text actually tells us the reason Esau did this.

15:24.349 --> 15:29.074
Back in verse 34, Esau despised his birthright.

15:30.082 --> 15:36.492
So it's not saying that he despised his birthright after the fact because he had given it away.

15:37.294 --> 15:42.522
It's saying the reason he gave it away in the first place was because he despised it.

15:44.205 --> 15:47.109
Meaning he didn't consider it valuable.

15:48.351 --> 15:54.141
He saw it as something that wasn't that big of a deal and didn't matter that much.

15:56.685 --> 15:57.586
And the point

15:57.698 --> 16:02.265
that the story is making is, man, was he wrong.

16:03.907 --> 16:06.832
He clearly makes a terrible decision here.

16:07.653 --> 16:21.554
And the story's told in such a way that anybody who reads it would recognize that Esau, even if he was manipulated and taken advantage of by his younger brother, makes one of the worst decisions of all time here, right?

16:21.574 --> 16:24.758
He gives up his birthright for a bowl of red stuff.

16:25.039 --> 16:27.282
He tears up the $100 million check

16:27.426 --> 16:28.527
and eats the blueberry.

16:30.289 --> 16:41.662
Now, of course, it's easy to look at him and laugh, but we would also do well to look at ourselves and to see if we've ever done anything like this.

16:42.763 --> 16:44.185
So let me ask you a few questions.

16:44.925 --> 16:51.453
Have you ever made a short-term decision without thinking through the long-term consequences?

16:53.215 --> 16:56.338
Have you ever gotten your priorities mixed up?

16:57.090 --> 17:01.274
and been careless with someone or something that mattered to you?

17:03.257 --> 17:10.184
Have you ever gone with the flow and done the easy thing instead of the right thing?

17:12.346 --> 17:18.913
Or have you ever chosen what felt good in the moment only to regret it later?

17:21.276 --> 17:21.877
Of course you have.

17:22.838 --> 17:23.338
So have I.

17:24.419 --> 17:25.581
That's the point of the story.

17:26.261 --> 17:26.962
All of us

17:27.298 --> 17:35.849
our Esau, which is why this story was passed down amongst the Israelites for generations.

17:37.130 --> 17:41.876
The elders would share this story with their community around the campfire.

17:42.317 --> 17:45.801
Parents would tell this story to their kids when they tucked a minute night.

17:46.342 --> 17:49.726
Pastors would preach this story to their congregations.

17:51.348 --> 17:55.954
And we actually have an example of this in the book of Hebrews.

17:56.514 --> 17:57.515
in the New Testament.

17:58.557 --> 18:06.047
Most Bible scholars think that Hebrews wasn't originally written as a letter or as an epistle, but it was actually a sermon.

18:07.028 --> 18:17.903
And in this sermon, the preacher uses the story of Jacob and Esau as a warning not to choose the easy thing over the best thing.

18:19.565 --> 18:26.194
Here's what he says in Hebrews chapter 12 verse 16, see that no one is sexually immoral

18:26.402 --> 18:34.254
or as godless like Esau, who for a single meal sold his inheritance rights as the oldest son.

18:36.537 --> 18:38.520
This is so interesting.

18:39.542 --> 18:43.307
This is not where I thought this story was gonna go.

18:44.709 --> 18:50.338
But whenever we can, we let the Bible interpret the Bible, right?

18:51.059 --> 18:55.826
And this is how the Old Testament story of Esau is applied

18:56.130 --> 19:15.279
by this New Testament preacher as a wise warning, not just about how we are to steward our lives in general, but specifically about how we as followers of Jesus would steward our bodies and our sexuality.

19:17.483 --> 19:24.914
So interesting because Esau's sin in Genesis 25 clearly wasn't sexual in nature.

19:24.994 --> 19:25.274
Right?

19:25.495 --> 19:28.700
He just wanted a bowl of soup.

19:28.720 --> 19:39.839
But it seems to me that the author of Hebrews is saying that sometimes we can be tempted to do the same things with our bodies as Esau did with his birthright.

19:42.423 --> 19:51.058
So remember that the root of Esau's sin was that he didn't recognize how valuable his birthright was.

19:51.970 --> 19:54.856
He didn't understand how much it mattered.

19:56.299 --> 20:05.119
And so rather than being careful and wise and intentional with it, he was careless and foolish and impulsive.

20:07.143 --> 20:10.290
And we're told in the end that Esau regretted what he had done.

20:11.106 --> 20:26.441
And so it's with like parental wisdom and pastoral care that the preacher in Hebrews warns followers of Jesus not to make that same mistake when it comes to what we do with our bodies and our sexuality.

20:28.663 --> 20:31.305
Here's how Eugene Peterson translates the same passage.

20:32.326 --> 20:40.274
Watch out for the Esau syndrome, trading away God's lifelong gift in order to satisfy a short-term appetite.

20:40.898 --> 20:46.205
You well know how Esau later regretted that impulsive act and wanted God's blessing.

20:46.706 --> 20:50.591
But by then it was too late, tears or no tears.

20:54.677 --> 21:00.825
So notice how carefully and compassionately the author of Hebrews talks about this stuff.

21:01.947 --> 21:05.431
He's not coming down on his readers with judgment or with shame.

21:05.471 --> 21:10.418
He's not condemning anyone or trying to make anyone feel guilty for their mistakes.

21:10.850 --> 21:23.449
No, he's gently warning them to pay close attention to what they do with their bodies and their sexuality, because these things are valuable.

21:24.731 --> 21:26.233
These things matter.

21:27.776 --> 21:31.501
They matter not just to us, but it matters to God.

21:33.705 --> 21:37.170
And because God knows us and loves us and wants what's best for us,

21:38.722 --> 21:45.332
God has given us careful instructions for how we are to steward our bodies and our sexuality.

21:47.555 --> 21:50.119
We're gonna wade into this conversation for a few minutes.

21:52.022 --> 21:57.009
And I recognize how loaded and layered this topic is.

21:58.872 --> 22:08.466
Here at Antioch, we don't often address issues of sex, marriage, and gender directly from the front.

22:08.866 --> 22:26.071
And the reason for that is because in my 24 years of pastoring, I've found that private conversations are almost always better than public declarations when it comes to caring for the delicate parts of people's lives and stories.

22:28.494 --> 22:33.682
But I also know that these are questions that all of us are asking all the time these days.

22:34.658 --> 22:49.315
And since this is where the scripture leads us this week, we're gonna spend a few minutes exploring what the Bible teaches about how followers of Jesus can best steward their sexuality.

22:51.837 --> 22:52.198
All right?

22:54.600 --> 22:55.742
Back to verse 16.

22:56.763 --> 23:03.090
He says, see to it that no one is sexually immoral or is godless like Esau.

23:04.514 --> 23:09.639
So when the Bible talks about sexual immorality, what's it talking about?

23:10.880 --> 23:15.865
And if there's such thing as sexual immorality, then what is sexual morality?

23:17.227 --> 23:20.470
We've already established there's no model marriages in scripture.

23:21.211 --> 23:26.476
Like other than Jesus himself, we don't have any great examples to follow in this way.

23:26.556 --> 23:32.242
So we can't base our understanding of what the Bible teaches on sex by looking at the lives

23:32.354 --> 23:34.577
of the story of the characters in the stories.

23:34.997 --> 23:36.219
So where do we go then?

23:37.380 --> 23:44.309
Who do we look to to figure out how the Bible defines sexual morality and immorality?

23:44.449 --> 23:44.969
Where do we look?

23:46.051 --> 23:46.872
We look to Jesus.

23:48.834 --> 23:55.442
We go to Jesus and we look at how he lived and what he taught about these things.

23:56.962 --> 24:03.289
And when you go to Jesus and you look at his teachings, what you'll find is that this is a topic he wasn't afraid to address.

24:05.051 --> 24:08.014
He spoke often about these kinds of things.

24:08.094 --> 24:12.359
In fact, he himself uses the term sexual immorality.

24:13.220 --> 24:26.194
Like in Matthew 15, for example, Jesus says, for out of the heart come evil thoughts, murder, adultery, sexual immorality, theft, false testimony, slander, these,

24:26.338 --> 24:28.041
are what defile a person.

24:29.603 --> 24:34.070
Jesus uses the term sexual immorality in the Greek, it's poor Nea.

24:36.093 --> 24:40.259
And so the first thing we need to notice is that Jesus has something to say on this topic.

24:41.661 --> 24:46.929
He cares about what his followers do with their bodies.

24:48.531 --> 24:55.762
Sometimes we think, God doesn't care who I sleep with as long as I'm a loving and kind person and we take care of the poor.

24:56.738 --> 24:58.101
And those are all great things to do.

24:58.181 --> 25:02.731
But if you actually listen to what Jesus says, you'll find that he does care.

25:04.275 --> 25:14.578
And in fact, here he lists sexual immorality right along with some other pretty big types of sin that are all damaging to the human soul.

25:17.378 --> 25:22.245
So the question is, when Jesus talks about sexual immorality, what's he talking about?

25:22.485 --> 25:29.115
We could ask 100 different people how they define sexual morality or immorality, and we'd get 100 different answers.

25:29.836 --> 25:31.799
But how does Jesus define it?

25:31.819 --> 25:40.632
Well, if we jump ahead in Matthew, just a few chapters, we get to a place where some of Jesus' opponents are grilling him about sex and marriage.

25:41.713 --> 25:45.138
Matthew 19, some Pharisees came to him to test him.

25:45.666 --> 25:50.231
They asked, is it lawful for a man to divorce his wife for any and every reason?

25:51.212 --> 26:04.125
Haven't you read, Jesus replied, that at the beginning, the Creator made them male and female and said for this reason, a man will leave his father and mother and be united to his wife and the two will become one flesh.

26:05.126 --> 26:07.929
So they are no longer two, but one flesh.

26:08.769 --> 26:13.234
Therefore, what God has joined together, let no one separate.

26:15.330 --> 26:16.231
So interesting.

26:17.293 --> 26:23.463
When Jesus is asked about sexual morality, where does he go?

26:25.066 --> 26:27.530
He goes to Genesis one and two.

26:28.852 --> 26:32.157
He quotes from the first two chapters of the Bible.

26:32.297 --> 26:38.227
Again, the only place in the entire story of the Bible where things are the way they're supposed to be.

26:39.909 --> 26:42.834
And so for Jesus, his reference point,

26:43.458 --> 26:54.169
for his theology of sex and marriage isn't based on the Mosaic law or Levitical codes or anything like that, but it's based on Genesis one and two.

26:55.690 --> 27:02.077
And so if our question is how did Jesus define sexual morality, we could think about it like this.

27:03.438 --> 27:11.346
Jesus saw Genesis one and two as containing God's creational design for sex and marriage.

27:12.802 --> 27:21.795
And what you see in Genesis 1 and 2 in the garden is a man and a woman in a covenant union of marriage.

27:23.077 --> 27:25.320
He says, male and female, he created them.

27:26.061 --> 27:29.806
And a man will be united to his wife, and the two will become one flesh.

27:31.869 --> 27:37.417
This is where Jesus starts when it comes to questions about marriage and sex.

27:38.439 --> 27:40.722
And this is where the historic

27:41.154 --> 27:43.037
Christian view comes from as well.

27:44.218 --> 27:46.081
God's creational design.

27:48.263 --> 27:53.951
So if that's sexual morality, then how would Jesus define sexual immorality?

27:54.832 --> 27:58.337
What fits in to this phrase, poor Nea?

27:59.238 --> 28:07.529
Well, what you notice is that in Genesis one and two, we don't have a list of all the negative examples of sexual impurity.

28:08.851 --> 28:11.154
Instead, what we have is a vision

28:11.298 --> 28:12.740
of sexual purity.

28:14.102 --> 28:16.185
So what did Jesus mean by sexual immorality?

28:16.886 --> 28:24.075
Well, he meant any sexual relationship or activity outside of a man and woman in covenant marriage.

28:25.978 --> 28:38.034
You might think about it like this, all the different ways, all the different practices, all the different relationships that wouldn't fit that vision.

28:39.458 --> 28:47.089
So this is also the traditional Christian view that's been held almost universally by Christians throughout history.

28:47.870 --> 28:49.452
This is the view that I hold as well.

28:52.156 --> 29:02.450
And so if any sexual relationship or activity other than a husband and wife and in a covenant of marriage is sexual morality, then there are countless possibilities of what this could look like.

29:03.106 --> 29:05.189
You see them all throughout the story of the Bible.

29:05.549 --> 29:08.133
You see them in every human society around the world.

29:08.513 --> 29:12.739
We have come up with all kinds of ways to be sexually immoral.

29:14.562 --> 29:17.546
Some of those ways are more obvious than others.

29:19.368 --> 29:21.611
Some are more subtle.

29:21.631 --> 29:24.054
Some are publicly celebrated.

29:25.536 --> 29:27.940
Others are locked behind closed doors.

29:29.682 --> 29:32.626
Some forms of sexual morality are actually

29:33.186 --> 29:40.393
tender and consensual, and others are abusive or violent.

29:41.794 --> 29:46.099
So it's not that all forms of sexual immorality are equal to each other.

29:47.200 --> 29:54.627
It's that nothing outside this circle is what God intended in the garden when he created humans as relational and sexual beings.

29:57.590 --> 30:02.034
So if sexual immorality includes any sexual relationship or activity,

30:02.210 --> 30:04.212
other than a man and woman in covenant marriage.

30:04.893 --> 30:14.442
And according to Jesus, that even includes lusting after someone in our heart or with our eyes, then here's my question for you.

30:16.103 --> 30:19.447
Who in this room can claim sexual morality?

30:25.492 --> 30:27.875
Who here would claim to be without sin?

30:29.356 --> 30:31.218
Who's lived their entire life?

30:31.970 --> 30:34.573
perfectly inside that little circle of morality.

30:36.115 --> 30:43.464
No one, none of us, none of us can claim that we have lived a sexually moral life.

30:43.684 --> 30:49.091
Every single one of us has sinned and fallen short of the glory of God in this way.

30:49.652 --> 30:51.914
My immorality may be different than yours.

30:52.034 --> 31:01.586
Mine may be more visible than yours or more public than yours or more obvious than yours, but none of us can claim moral superiority to anyone else.

31:01.986 --> 31:06.292
Now, I may not have had sex outside of marriage, but it's not like I had a lot of offers.

31:11.300 --> 31:17.089
We have all given up our birth rights for a bowl of soup.

31:18.391 --> 31:22.176
We have all torn up the check and chosen the blueberry.

31:23.138 --> 31:24.981
All of us are Esau.

31:26.883 --> 31:31.250
And that's the paradoxical brilliance of Jesus' teaching on this.

31:31.682 --> 31:34.345
because he takes sexual sins seriously.

31:35.126 --> 31:39.272
And he says it matters because it will defile your soul.

31:41.054 --> 31:48.764
And at the same time, he doesn't allow for anyone or any group of people to exclude themselves from the community of sinners.

31:50.766 --> 31:59.858
What this means is that there is no biblical basis for elevating one kind of sexual immorality to a higher level over any other.

32:00.898 --> 32:10.191
And we all know that Christians have a well-earned reputation for fearing, excluding, condemning, and demonizing certain groups of people.

32:11.754 --> 32:14.718
But Jesus doesn't teach anything like that.

32:16.881 --> 32:21.428
Instead, he asks, who wants to throw the first stone?

32:27.717 --> 32:28.658
We all have sinned.

32:30.210 --> 32:31.952
We all are like Esau.

32:34.736 --> 32:35.337
Great.

32:35.357 --> 32:36.218
So where does that leave us?

32:36.238 --> 32:39.262
Do we just acknowledge the world is broken?

32:39.322 --> 32:41.484
We all suck and that's the way it is.

32:44.728 --> 32:46.811
Well, that's never been the invitation of the gospel.

32:48.573 --> 32:54.281
Jesus invites all of us to come to Him just as we are.

32:55.843 --> 32:58.546
No matter where we've been, no matter what we've done.

32:59.682 --> 33:01.605
The gospel levels the playing field.

33:02.586 --> 33:05.130
We've all sinned, we all need Jesus.

33:06.412 --> 33:12.280
We all have places of guilt or shame or regret over our sexual sin.

33:12.781 --> 33:15.965
And just like Esau, we can't change what we've done.

33:15.986 --> 33:17.688
Tears are no tears.

33:20.352 --> 33:21.293
But here's the good news.

33:23.917 --> 33:27.442
God isn't nearly as concerned about where you've been,

33:28.226 --> 33:29.709
as he is about where you're headed.

33:32.694 --> 33:34.477
The question isn't where you're starting from.

33:34.517 --> 33:37.923
The question is, which way are you going?

33:40.147 --> 33:41.329
You can think about it like this.

33:43.332 --> 33:53.810
Wherever you find yourself, the invitation of the gospel is that disciples of Jesus, starting from wherever they are,

33:54.434 --> 34:01.224
would move towards sexual wholeness and holiness by the power of the Holy Spirit.

34:02.906 --> 34:15.625
So wherever you find yourself today, whatever your life has looked like, however you identify, whatever you've done, whatever has been done to you, none of that defines your identity.

34:17.548 --> 34:22.034
And none of that disqualifies you from the redeeming grace of Christ.

34:22.402 --> 34:28.290
He loves you and he wants you and he's calling you to come and find life in his name.

34:31.795 --> 34:44.792
So I want you to know that if you're someone who's struggling with sexual sin or temptation, you're not alone and you're welcome here.

34:47.115 --> 34:49.138
And if you today find yourself

34:50.562 --> 34:59.592
In any kind of relationship or life situation that falls outside the biblical vision, you can't change the past.

35:01.394 --> 35:07.621
So receive the grace and forgiveness of Jesus and figure out where he's leading you from here.

35:09.203 --> 35:15.250
I don't know what that looks like for you, but the spirit will lead you.

35:16.642 --> 35:22.230
Because ultimately, the Christian life isn't about moving toward morality.

35:23.071 --> 35:27.056
It's about moving towards Jesus.

35:27.076 --> 35:29.940
It's about being with Him and becoming like Him.

35:29.960 --> 35:34.266
It's about being loved by Him and learning to love as He loves us.

35:34.847 --> 35:39.052
The gospel isn't a call to morality, sexual or otherwise.

35:39.473 --> 35:41.556
It's a call to a person.

35:43.318 --> 35:46.162
A person who knows what it's like.

35:48.066 --> 36:04.266
Hebrews 4, 15 says, we don't have a high priest in Jesus who is unable to empathize with our weaknesses, but we have one who has been tempted in every way, has been tempted in every way, every way just as we are.

36:06.109 --> 36:07.510
Yet he did not sin.

36:07.570 --> 36:16.882
Do you know Jesus lived 33 years as a celibate single man?

36:19.746 --> 36:29.719
And Jesus, just like every single one of us, had to deal with unwanted or unfulfilled sexual desires.

36:31.461 --> 36:34.425
He knows exactly what it's like.

36:36.387 --> 36:37.489
And yet he did not sin.

36:39.651 --> 36:48.082
So it shouldn't surprise us then that Jesus says, if we're going to follow him, then we're going to have to get used

36:48.194 --> 36:49.556
to denying ourselves.

36:53.180 --> 36:56.043
There's a brilliant pastor in the UK named Sam Albury.

36:57.624 --> 37:02.129
And as a single man, he's committed to a life of celibacy.

37:03.671 --> 37:04.832
Here's what he says about it.

37:06.354 --> 37:11.840
As someone in this situation, what Jesus calls me to do is exactly what he calls anyone to do.

37:12.941 --> 37:17.106
I am to deny myself, take up my cross, and follow him.

37:18.018 --> 37:20.944
every Christian is called to costly sacrifice.

37:21.746 --> 37:30.343
A number of Christians have said something like this, the gospel must be harder for you than it is for me, as though I have more to give up than they do.

37:31.606 --> 37:35.634
But the fact is that the gospel demands everything of all of us.

37:36.354 --> 37:48.588
If someone thinks the gospel is somehow slotted into their life quite easily without causing any major adjustments to their lifestyle or aspirations, it is likely that they have not really started following Jesus at all.

37:51.532 --> 37:55.997
See, following Jesus isn't about self-fulfillment, it's about self-denial.

37:57.499 --> 38:03.986
It's about saying no to our strongest desires so we can say yes to our deepest desires.

38:06.274 --> 38:16.087
And that is what the Bible teaches about how we can best steward our bodies and our sexuality as a gift from God.

38:20.653 --> 38:21.434
But here's a question.

38:23.436 --> 38:24.918
What if someone disagrees with us?

38:27.622 --> 38:34.130
What if someone holds a different view than we do about marriage and sex and gender?

38:35.842 --> 38:38.385
What if somebody thinks that our view is wrong?

38:42.190 --> 38:45.915
That's okay.

38:45.935 --> 38:46.436
It really is.

38:47.597 --> 38:48.158
That's okay.

38:50.781 --> 38:51.863
Here's what I tell my kids.

38:53.505 --> 38:57.030
When it comes to living as followers of Jesus in this world, two things.

38:57.130 --> 38:59.733
Number one, we love everyone.

39:01.235 --> 39:03.538
Every single person we meet is our neighbor.

39:04.162 --> 39:14.134
And no matter who they are or how they look or how they identify or what they do, we treat every single person with love, respect, compassion and kindness.

39:14.334 --> 39:16.677
No matter what, we love everyone always.

39:18.439 --> 39:23.526
And number two, we don't expect everyone to see the world the way we do.

39:25.828 --> 39:30.354
Lots of people live and believe differently than us as followers of Jesus.

39:31.490 --> 39:36.097
So we can't expect non-Christians to live according to Christian teachings.

39:37.599 --> 39:42.386
Like we have a hard enough time following Jesus and we have the spirit of God living in us.

39:45.731 --> 39:53.683
So we do our best to live what we believe and we love those who live and believe differently than we do.

39:54.805 --> 39:55.466
That's how we do it.

39:59.632 --> 40:01.074
And what about in here?

40:02.594 --> 40:08.880
I know that there are plenty of you who might disagree with something I've said today or the way I've said it.

40:11.222 --> 40:11.923
That's okay too.

40:15.546 --> 40:16.287
You're welcome here.

40:17.909 --> 40:18.830
We can still hang out.

40:23.474 --> 40:31.762
Because our hope isn't in being right or being better or winning a culture war

40:32.322 --> 40:41.592
or taking our country back, or running away and escaping from the world, our hope is in the unshakable kingdom of Jesus.

40:44.035 --> 40:44.896
And he's got this.

40:46.978 --> 40:47.699
And he's got you.

40:50.662 --> 40:56.008
So come, say yes to this meal that he's prepared for us this week.

40:57.450 --> 40:57.810
Amen.

